<TEXT>
some might think a television show about 
home renovation would be as exciting as watching paint dry but 
pbs this old house has long since proved that americans love 
to watch other people fix up fixeruppers 
now this old house has this new host steve thomas an 
eclectic blend of thor heyerdahl ralph waldo emerson and robert 
redford 
pbs officials hope that thomas 36 an expert sailor carpenter 
world traveler and writer will dispel the whiff of scandal that 
hovered over the show when its original host bob vila left over a 
conflict of interest 
the popular vila began as cohost of the show with master 
carpenter norm abram 11 years ago he left after last season when 
an underwriter withdrew funding in a dispute over vilas commercial 
endorsements 
the show is produced at wgbhtv in boston and is broadcast more 
than 500 times a week by 315 pbs stations across the country 
reaching 15 million viewers and standing as public televisions 
highestrated halfhour show 
the new season of this old house premiered in some parts of 
the country last weekend and will be seen in other places later 
this week 
vilas departure prompted a flurry of more than 400 videotapes 
and resumes from people vying for the job about half the 
applicants were television professionals others had little more 
than rudimentary carpentry credentials and a pickup truck a 
concert pianist and a brain surgeon were among those interested 
but the man who won the job never applied thomas who had 
almost no oncamera television experience was in northwest alaska 
researching his new book on the arctic during the search for vilas 
successor 
he had returned to the 1836 colonial revival house he shares 
with his wife and 3yearold son on bostons north shore and was in 
the middle of his own renovation project constructing skylights 
when he got a call from wgbh publicist daphne noyes 
noyes was calling about thomas film the last navigator 
which aired on pbs stations in july but during the phone call she 
mentioned that vilas job was open and suggested thomas apply for 
the job 
ten days and one screen test later thomas who combines 
heyerdahls sailing zeal with emersons philosophical selfreliance 
and redfords telegenic good looks had the job 
thomas the grandson of a missionary who worked with eskimos in 
isolated point hope alaska appears to have inherited the hardy 
stock of his forebears 
since graduating from evergreen state college in olympia wash 
thomas has built boats worked construction skippered ships across 
the atlantic and pacific studied ancient celestial navigation with 
a master navigator written a book and helped produce a pbs film 
his latest project is a book about the arctic region where his 
father was born called the wilderness of ice and mind 
but thomas is fairly modest about his accomplishments 
basically im a bum he said in a recent interview in 
concord where he and abram will be dismantling an 1835 barn for 
most of this years show turning it into a singlefamily home 
ive done a bunch of different stuff there are those who would 
say ive never had a regular job 
thomas has supported himself since college by avoiding the 
office and desk grind he grew up in southern california where he 
learned to sail and surf early he also learned home renovation 
firsthand from his father who fixed up houses and sold them 
after college he sailed and raced extensively around the world 
during a 1979 voyage between the galapagos and the marquesas 
islands in the remote pacific without electronic navigation 
instruments thomas lost the nautical equivalent of an odometer and 
had to rely on his eyes to measure the speed of the boat 
i found i could do it accurately he recalled i decided i 
wanted to become completely selfreliant 
his desire to learn ancient navigation led him to a master 
navigator in micronesia who spoke only satawalese thomas learned 
the language enough to understand the navigator during a yearlong 
apprenticeship 
he later wrote the last navigator about the experience it 
became a segment for pbs adventure series 
thomas said he spent a weekend considering the this old 
house job and whether or not theyd even want me for it 
once he was hired thomas said he stuck close to the shows 
creator and producer russell morash and operated on fear and 
adrenaline he has done eight shows so far and said he has grown 
more comfortable in front of the camera 
thomas said morash talked about a 10year commitment and that 
sounded fine to me he calls the job with its july to march 
shooting schedule ideal for a writer and craftsman 
i have a tremendous respect and admiration for true 
craftsmanship the way a person unites his craft with the rest of 
his life its pretty amazing you can communicate something you 
feel deeply about and thats part of this job 
</TEXT>
