<TEXT>
along a dimly lit east berlin thoroughfare 
apartment dwellers wave sparklers cheer and applaud from 
balconies urging on thousands of people demonstrating for 
democratic reform 
in a crowded smokefilled bar a young man shouts happy 
birthday police state and his companions assail the repressive 
policies of the hardline communist government 
they jeer at weekend celebrations marking the states 40th 
anniversary 
in the most dramatic show of public dissatisfaction in more than 
three decades east germans have sent a clear message to the aging 
leadership they want reform and momentum for change is growing 
at least 50000 east germans gave up hope that the orthodox 
communist government was capable of change and have fled west since 
midseptember in the largest such exodus since the berlin wall was 
built in 1961 
for many left behind anger over the governments intolerance of 
change and dissent came into full force as authorities trumpeted 
four decades of achievements in elaborate ceremonies 
public discontent translated into massive street protests in 
east berlin and at least five provincial cities on a scale that 
hadnt been seen since a 1953 workers revolt was crushed by soviet 
tanks 
they east germanys leaders have ignored and underestimated 
just how many people are fed up with this lousy system said a 
30yearold east german woman who asked not to be identified 
because she feared reprisal 
hope for change has taken on new urgency as democratic reform 
sweeps the soviet union poland and hungary east germans hope 
soviet president mikhail s gorbachev can help bring change to this 
country of 166 million 
but east german leaders have rejected the need for change and 
routinely suppress fledgling opposition groups prominent 
opposition activists are frequently expelled to west germany 
open dissent has traditionally been suppressed swiftly and 
brutally by security forces but the weekend crushing of street 
protests was the most violent in recent memory 
the only people who are satisfied here are people who reap 
party privileges one man said 
the communist party controls most aspects of everyday life and 
although east germans enjoy a higher standard of living than their 
east bloc neighbors the atmosphere is clouded by gloom and a sense 
of powerlessness 
many complain of the severe restrictions imposed on travel to 
the west even within the east bloc czechoslovakia was the only 
country east germans could travel to freely then last week that 
border was closed 
the mass emigration of east germans that helped stir the recent 
protests is a principal topic of conversation in east berlin 
its not easy to give up everything and leave friends and 
family behind said a 24yearold waitress 
others weigh the achievements in some spheres against life in a 
repressive state 
most east germans would say that they are proud of many of the 
social benefits socialism has brought to the people said a 
27yearold university student referring to free daycare and 
medical treatment 
but a joyless restricted life is the price were paying for 
it 
those who have decided to stay and work for change are buoyed by 
new opposition groups and the spontaneous support for the 
prodemocracy demonstrations 
i still have hope said a 35yearold east berlin man who 
said he was fired from an adminstrative job after openly defending 
a human rights group this is only the beginning 
