<TEXT>
city and civil rights leaders lauded an 
antidiscrimination housing settlement but they disagreed on 
bostons progress in overcoming the racial strife that flared in 
the mid1970s with courtordered busing 
the settlement announced last week stemmed from a 1988 suit 
filed by the national association for the advancement of colored 
people it alleged that more than 2000 minority families were 
discouraged from applying for housing in predominantly white 
developments or were denied such housing 
the agreement provides up to 2500 for families who were passed 
over it also affirms a housing plan adopted last year to give 
priority to those who were discriminated against in tenant 
selection 
in addition a community benefit fund estimated at 
500000 will supply grants to encourage integration and 
multicultural activities in the citys public housing developments 
naacp officials said the settlement was a landmark agreement 
since those who suffered discrimination will receive financial 
compensation 
it was designed to show that if you do wrong youre going to 
pay for it said benjamin hooks the national executive director 
of the naacp 
mayor raymond flynn said the pact would end a painful era 
this is the last barrier that remains that goes back to the 
turbulent 1970s and 80s flynn said hopefully this will wipe 
the slate clean and everyone will be on a level playing field for 
housing 
but others said the legacy of bostons racially troubled past 
when the city erupted in violence over school desegregation was 
still alive just not as obvious 
what youre having is fewer rocks being thrown and there 
arent demonstrations and rhetoric but underneath it all there 
still is the cause said mel king a back leader and professor of 
community development at the massachusetts institute of technology 
hooks said the root cause for housing inequity is pure and 
simple racism 
he added id like to think there was a change of heart but 
that i dont know but at least in boston theyre willing to uphold 
the law 
flynn said much of the housing problems can be blamed on the 
failure to implement a policy adopted in 1978 that was intended to 
provide open housing for minorities 
officials did not follow through on the policy he said 
because they could not ensure the safety of minorities moving 
into neighborhoods 
just four years earlier the busing of black students into 
predominantly white south boston prompted protests rock throwing 
and the flight of white students to private schools 
