<TEXT>
the bowler hat enduring symbol of the englishman 
is catching the fancy of americans 
although it has been disappearing from londons financial 
district where it once was common exports of bowlers are growing 
particularly to the united states experts say 
theres been a marked increase in the number being sold to 
americans said richard stephenson managing director of the 
picadilly hatters james lock and co 
there is also demand from france where gray bowlers are worn to 
the horse races and from australia and africa 
overall sales are 25 percent higher than in the mid1980s with 
most of the growth coming from foreign sales stephenson said 
we are selling more said derek bedford managing director 
of christy and co britains biggest hat maker 
in britain today however bowlerwearers are viewed by some as 
mildly eccentric 
david green an 89yearold insurance underwriter explained why 
he has worn one for 65 years 
they are smart it used to be when people dressed smartly the 
proper thing to wear was a bowler ive just kept on with it 
bowlers also are good to grow geraniums in he said 
bedford attributes the recent upturn to increased demand for 
bowlers as riding hats and as womens fashion head wear 
we have seen some sort of designer ranges in very strong 
colors with holes cut in them and bells sewed on them bedford 
said you do see some very odd derivatives 
bowlers cost 113 to 139 each and americans are not buying 
them as a gimmick or for souvenirs stephenson said 
the vast majority are buying this with every intention of 
wearing it but bedford said we are really finding in the home 
market things quieter than we would like 
made of rabbit fur hardened with shellac bowlers still are 
handcrafted through 47 steps over the course of eight weeks 
bedford said 
the hats date back to 1850 when william coke a norfolk farmer 
asked james lock to make a hard hat that would protect his 
gamekeepers from overhead branches while they rode their horses 
lock designed a closefitting domed hat and had it made by 
london hatters thomas and william bowler 
according to bowler lore coke tried out the hat by jumping on 
it 
james lock has sold the hard hats ever since calling them cokes 
after the first customer but the bowler brothers also branched out 
on their own and their name stuck 
in the united states the hat became known as a derby because it 
was worn to the kentucky derby horse race 
in 1880s britain it became fashionable to wear a bowler in 
town and it was popular among lawyers brokers and bankers 
its particularly associated with london the pinstriped suit 
the rolled umbrella and the bowler hat stephenson said 
but they also were worn by offduty army officers and by the 
foremen of shipyards and mills in northern england 
they still are part of the uniform worn on parade by the orange 
order of northern ireland protestants 
the duke of windsor sometimes wore a bowler as did charlie 
chaplin winston churchill wore a squarecrowned variation 
during the 1920s and 1930s up to a million bowlers were 
produced annually in factories around stockport and manchester in 
northwest england 
the bowler went into decline after world war ii the spread of 
cars meant people didnt need hats as much to keep warm and dress 
became less formal 
after the war christy bought the failing stockport factories 
which altogether employed 3500 people christy currently has 350 
employees making all kinds of hats including some 50000 bowlers a 
year 
