raw like sushi virgin neneh cherry 
 
in the postmadonna era danceoriented female singers seem a 
dime a dozen but newcomer neneh cherry seems to have the talent to 
stand out in the crowd 
the young londonbased singers raw like sushi is a fresh 
mix of pop rap and house music with a bravado sure to appeal to 
girls growing up in a changing world 
the debut album has a shimmering urban sound firmly 
contemporary but avoiding the cliches that are rife in this genre 
cherry samples a variety of found sounds such as malcolm 
mclarens buffalo girls on her own buffalo stance and 
stevie wonders living for the city 
cherry herself a mother sternly defends the rights of children 
on the next generation she calls on fathers to stand up for 
their parental responsibilities and society to fix crumbling school 
systems 
whats this sitting on my lap she asks its the next 
generation 
buffalo stance is already a hit and kisses on the wind 
is high on the charts now both deservedly so manchild a 
ballad with a combination of singing and rapping and the 
toughminded heart are both noteworthy 
cherry is a serviceable singer but an even better rapper with a 
sassy style 
if shes not yet ready to challenge madonna for her crown at 
least cherry can keep the blond one company on the charts for 
awhile 
by david bauder associated press writer 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
missa prolationum marian motets by johannes ockeghem the 
hilliard ensemble emi 
 
little is known about johannes ockeghem 14201477 he spent 
much of his adult life serving the kings of france and achieved a 
lofty reputation among musicians of the day and in later centuries 
ockeghems total known output consists of 20 chansons 12 masses 
three partial masses and a handful of motets 
he also came to have the reputation of dry academician because 
of his mastery of composition the beauty of this mass shows 
clearly the opposite especially with the feeling interpretation by 
the hilliard ensemble made up of two altos three tenors a 
baritone and two basses 
the missa prolationum perhaps ockeghems greatest work is a 
landmark the first mass to use a canon or successively repeated 
melody in all its parts paired or individual voices sing the 
same melody but in different meters and intervals 
in the bigger picture of music history ockeghem represents a 
new kind of musical thinking a departure from the idea of a basic 
melody around which music is constructed and a move towards using 
an ideagenerating theme that unifies an entire pieces development 
the performance here is just right the atmosphere is 
otherworldly and serene but not cold the singers are absolutely 
precise in their joint entrances and phraseendings chords burst 
forth like a flood of light through a cathedrals rose window and 
solo voices weave a tapestry of sound one minor caveat perhaps 
because of the recording conditions sybillant consonants seem to 
jump out of the texture creating a distracting effect 
by daniel j wakin associated press writer 
</TEXT>
