business optimism appears to be dimming and manufacturers are 
becoming more aggressive in cutting costs and people but a 
relatively steady unemployment rate which has fluctuated between 
51 percent and 53 percent since april means somebody is hiring 
the question is who 
steven haugen an economist with the bureau of labor statistics 
says job growth is concentrated in the service sector that broad 
amorphous category covering everything from data processing to 
theme parks to the neighborhood beauty parlor experts say this 
sector is creating upwards of 15 million jobs a year 
services is very labor intensive so its sucking up all the 
workers said john hekman a senior economist at the claremont 
economics institute in claremont calif 
in september alone when the loss of 103000 manufacturing jobs 
inched the unemployment rate up 01 percent to 53 percent service 
industries added 317000 jobs a closer look however shows 
